\begin_layout Standard
\align center

\series bold
\color red
There's no branching systems because it's impossible for an arborescence
 rooted at 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{2}$
\end_inset

 to be a spanning subgraph of the original graph (no arborescence rooted
 at 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{2}$
\end_inset

 can contain all of the original graph's vertices).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center

\series bold
\color blue
We also have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
J_{1} & =\{\emptyset,\{A\}\}\\
J_{2} & =P\{A,B;C\}\\
 & =\{\emptyset,A,B,C,\{A,B\},\{A,C\},\{B,C\},\{A,B,C\}\}.
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center

\series bold
\color blue
The bases of 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{2}$
\end_inset

 (which are associated with 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{2}$
\end_inset

 respectively) are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathcal{B}(M_{1}) & =\{\{A\}\}\\
\mathcal{B}(M_{2}) & =\{\{A,B,C\}\}.
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center

\series bold
\color blue
So we have that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{B}(M_{1})\cap\mathcal{B}(M_{2})=\emptyset.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center

\series bold
\color blue
meaning that no branching systems exist, which is exactly what we said at
 the beginning!
\end_layout

